                            <comment id="12517241" author="johnemb" created="Thu, 2 Aug 2007 13:38:09 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Attaching patch (d2988_v1.diff, d2988_v1.stat) adding a max heap size setting in the junit-core target of the top-level build.xml file. The setting is: &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;maxmemory=&quot;512m&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This eliminates junitreport-related OutOfMemoryErrors in my environment (Solaris 10 x86, Sun JVM 1.4.2 and 1.5), sane build.&lt;br/&gt;
Reviews are appreciated &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.gif&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12517292" author="bryanpendleton" created="Thu, 2 Aug 2007 16:35:32 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks John! This seems like a good idea to me. I&apos;ll have a look at committing this change over the weekend. If anyone feels this is a bad idea, please let us know.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12517642" author="bryanpendleton" created="Fri, 3 Aug 2007 23:19:45 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks John! The change worked perfectly in my environment, which had been routinely experiencing the out-of-memory errors before. It is very nice to get a 100% pass rate on &quot;ant junitreport&quot;. Committed the change to the trunk as svn revision 562604.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12518337" author="johnemb" created="Wed, 8 Aug 2007 06:22:18 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Thank you for committing, Bryan! The fix is in the trunk, so I&apos;m closing the issue.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
